On Friday , Japan 's Cabinet Office released GDP data for the 4th quarter of 2005 . 
After price adjustment , actual growth in GDP in the October - December quarter was up 1.4 % from the previous quarter , registering a growth rate that was 1.2 % higher than expected . 
The primary reasons are strong domestic demand and rising exports to major countries , such as China and the United States . This is a sign of a sustained economic recovery . 
This is the fourth quarter in a row that Japan has witnessed economic growth and the highest growth rate since the first and third quarters of 2005 . It is primarily due to individual spending , capital expenditure and strong exports . 
In addition , Japan 's central bank will end in April its extremely loose currency policy of the past five years , thereby encouraging the financial market 's expectations for an economic upturn . 
In October through December , nongovernmental consumption increased by 0.8 % thanks to a moderate improvement in the unemployment rate and wages . 
The NIKKEI climbed after the release of the GDP figures , but was down 0.74 % at the close of the morning session . 
Japanese Yen fell after a short - lived appreciation and transaction prices hovered around 118.15 yen to 1 USD . 
