< HEADLINE > Military Observation : How Long Can Iran Hold Out under US Air Attacks ? 
< POSTER > Yun Feiquan 
If we describe conventional war of attrition as causing the opponent to bleed to death , then from the outset modern warfare consists of shooting a gun toward the opponent 's head in order to render him a " vegetable " even before there is time to bleed . 
The disparity between the military capabilities of Iran and the US is not one of quantity , but rather in the understanding of modern war . 
Iran , which fought a victorless eight - year war with Iraq , seems not yet to have understood the true significance of modern hi - tech warfare . 
Following an analysis of US military deployments , Britain 's " International Intelligence - - Commentary " recently said that the US military is carrying out preparations to launch a large scale air assault on Iran ...... 
The current status of Iran 's air force is cause for concern . 
The present situation of Iran 's air force is quite similar to that of Iraq 's air force prior to the 2003 war . 
The country does not possess the capacity to research and develop modern weapons on its own and is also under an arms embargo imposed by the west . 
Once war breaks out , it is uncertain whether the antiquated planes in Iran 's air force will be able to take to the air to engage US forces . 
At present , Iran 's air - defense system consists primarily of an air force belonging to Iran 's regular forces , the land - based air - defense force and the air - defense capacity of the revolutionary guard . 
Of these , Iran 's air force presently has a manpower of 50,000 and more than 300 aircraft of various models . 
The most important aircraft models include US - manufactured F-4 Phantoms , F5 Tigers , F-14 Tomcats and Russian - manufactured Mig-29s . 
The land - based air - defense force is primarily equipped with surface - to - air missiles of the US - manufactured Hawk series and the British Rapier series , as well as a portion belong to the Russian - manufactured SAM series . 
With regards to the current status of Iran 's air - defense strength , analysis by individuals such as the US military expert Harold Hutchison and military expert [ Hela Muqixin ] of the [ Russian Political and Military Research Institute ] indicates that , viewed from the present situation , there are still holes in Iran 's air - defense capabilities and air - defense system . 
Hutchison says that with respect to overall capabilities , Iran 's air force simply is not on the same level as the US air force . 
A large number of the US - manufactured jetfighters that Iran is equipped with cannot be used because of a lack of spare parts and upgrading . 
The F-14 fighter was once the trump card of Iran 's air force , but today there are only ten or so that are able to fly . 
The dependability in actual combat of the AIM-54 Phoenix missiles they carry , known for their ultra - long distance attack capabilities , is also doubtful . 
[ Hela Muqixin ] points out however that the air - defense missile systems provided to Iran by the US in the 1970s and 1980s have lost their warfare capabilities because of a lack of spare parts . 
In addition , the other non - systematic air - defense weapons obtained from Russia and other countries are simply incapable of countering US forces possessing powerful electromagnetic countermeasure capabilities . 
Scraping Together a Military Affects Battle Capability 
Clearly , Iran 's government is also aware that its fate in a conflict depends upon whether it can defend the sky above and it has been carrying out eleventh - hour preparations by scraping together whatever it can find in order to build up its air - defense system . 
At present , its methods can be summarized into two devices : 
The first is an all - out effort to conceal key nuclear facilities and beef up their defense capabilities . 
According to a report in the British newspaper The Times , Iran has hidden the Natanz Nuclear Facility , the Isfahan Uranium Enrichment Center and other core components of their nuclear facilities eighteen meters underground and added a two - meter thick concrete protection shell . 
But the US military is one step ahead . As early as the 1991 Persian Gulf War , it saw the effectiveness of underground bunkers in anti - aircraft defense and rushed to develop various types of earth - penetrating bombs . 
After ten years of focused research , the US military has a full complement of strategies and weapons to counter reinforced underground bunkers . 
Iran has recently also bought a large amount of advanced air - defense weapons from Russia . 
Since the end of last year , Iran 's government has reached a series of agreements with Russia to purchase Pechora-2A air defense missile systems as well as 29 Tor-M1 air - defense missile systems valued at US $ 700m . 
However , modern warfare is a contest of system against system . 
The various air - attack weapons of the US military have all been developed by the country itself for its own benefit and , through many years of perfectioning in actual combat , they have been molded into an impressive war machine . 
On the other hand , Iran 's " up - to - date weapons " have been scraped together from other countries . Whether or not they can be made combat effective in such a short time is still in question . 
Iran 's Lags Behind Not Only in Weapons 
The concept of " air - land battle " was first raised in " Operations " , published by the US military in 1982 . It stresses reliance on strength in the air to carry out attacks against the enemy 's strategically valuable targets . This paralyses the other side 's command systems at the start of the war and turns the enemy 's conventional forces , even if they are superior , into a " slab of meat on a cutting board . " 
In the 1991 Persian Gulf War , the 1999 Kosovo War and the 2003 Iraq War , the US military did not concern itself with how many planes the opponent had , but rather the range of its own Tomahawk cruise missiles . 
Even if Iran 's government has prepared for a possible air attack and has begun to take steps to reinforce its air - defense capabilities , Iran , which fought to a stalemate in an eight - year war with Iraq , seems not to have fully understood the true meaning of modern hi - tech warfare . 
With the progress of the US military 's military transformation in recent years , the US military 's air - attack operations are completely different from the carpet bombing of the Vietnam War and instead rely on full - depth air assaults with various hi - tech weapons and modern information technology . 
Faced with this kind of air assault , how long Iran 's land - based air defense systems can hold out is an unknown . 
